//! String formatting utilities.
//!
//! This module provides behaviors and types for converting values to various
//! string representations, similar to Rust's `std::fmt` module.
//!
//! # Core Formatting Behaviors
//!
//! | Behavior | Description | Method | Example Output |
//! |----------|-------------|--------|----------------|
//! | [`Display`] | User-facing output | `to_string()` | `42`, `hello` |
//! | [`Debug`] | Developer-facing output | `debug_string()` | `Point { x: 10, y: 20 }` |
//! | [`Binary`] | Binary representation | `fmt_binary()` | `0b101010` |
//! | [`Octal`] | Octal representation | `fmt_octal()` | `0o52` |
//! | [`LowerHex`] | Lowercase hexadecimal | `fmt_lower_hex()` | `0x2a` |
//! | [`UpperHex`] | Uppercase hexadecimal | `fmt_upper_hex()` | `0x2A` |
//! | [`Pointer`] | Pointer address | `fmt_pointer()` | `0x7fff5fbff8c8` |
//! | [`LowerExp`] | Lowercase scientific | `fmt_lower_exp()` | `1.234e5` |
//! | [`UpperExp`] | Uppercase scientific | `fmt_upper_exp()` | `1.234E5` |
//!
//! # Display vs Debug
//!
//! The two most commonly used formatting behaviors are:
//!
//! - **[`Display`]**: For user-facing output. Should produce clean, readable text.
//! - **[`Debug`]**: For developer-facing output. Should show the internal structure.
//!
//! ```tml
//! use core::fmt::*
//!
//! let s = "hello"
//! println(s.to_string())      // hello (Display)
//! println(s.debug_string())   // "hello" (Debug - with quotes)
//!
//! let opt = Just(42)
//! println(opt.to_string())    // Just(42)
//! println(opt.debug_string()) // Just(42)
//! ```
//!
//! # Implementing Display and Debug
//!
//! For custom types, implement `Display` and `Debug`:
//!
//! ```tml
//! use core::fmt::{Display, Debug}
//!
//! pub type Point { x: I64, y: I64 }
//!
//! impl Display for Point {
//!     pub func to_string(this) -> Str {
//!         return "(" + this.x.to_string() + ", " + this.y.to_string() + ")"
//!     }
//! }
//!
//! impl Debug for Point {
//!     pub func debug_string(this) -> Str {
//!         return "Point { x: " + this.x.debug_string() + ", y: " + this.y.debug_string() + " }"
//!     }
//! }
//! ```
//!
//! # Debug Builders
//!
//! For complex types, use the debug builder helpers:
//!
//! ```tml
//! use core::fmt::{Debug, DebugStruct}
//!
//! impl Debug for MyStruct {
//!     pub func debug_string(this) -> Str {
//!         return DebugStruct::new("MyStruct")
//!             .field("name", this.name.debug_string())
//!             .field("value", this.value.debug_string())
//!             .finish()
//!     }
//! }
//! ```
//!
//! # Numeric Formatting
//!
//! Integer types support multiple representations:
//!
//! ```tml
//! use core::fmt::*
//!
//! let n: I32 = 42
//! println(n.to_string())       // "42" (decimal)
//! println(n.fmt_binary())      // "0b101010"
//! println(n.fmt_octal())       // "0o52"
//! println(n.fmt_lower_hex())   // "0x2a"
//! println(n.fmt_upper_hex())   // "0x2A"
//! ```
//!
//! # Formatting with Precision and Width
//!
//! Use the `Formatter` type for fine-grained control:
//!
//! ```tml
//! use core::fmt::*
//!
//! let mut fmt = Formatter::new()
//! fmt.set_width(10)
//! fmt.set_precision(2)
//! fmt.set_align(Alignment::Right)
//! fmt.set_fill(' ')
//!
//! let result = fmt.pad("42")  // "        42"
//! ```
//!
//! # Module Organization
//!
//! - `traits` - Core formatting behaviors (Display, Debug, etc.)
//! - `builders` - Debug builder helpers (DebugStruct, DebugList, etc.)
//! - `num` - Numeric formatting (Binary, Octal, Hex, Exp)
//! - `formatter` - Formatter type and formatting options
//! - `impls` - Implementations for primitive types
//! - `helpers` - Internal helper functions
//! - `rt` - Runtime formatting types (Argument, Count, FormatSpec)
//! - `float` - Floating-point formatting utilities
//!
//! All items are re-exported at the module root for convenience.

